[30;1m71 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m72 | [0m[35mGreenlets are cooperative (see **cooperative multitasking**) and sequential.[0m
[30;1m73 | [0m[35mThis means that when one greenlet is running, no other greenlet can be[0m
[30;1m74 | [0m[35mrunning; the programmer is fully in control of when execution switches between[0m
[30;1m75 | [0m[35mgreenlets. In other words ones, when using greenlets, should not expect[0m
[30;1m76 | [0m[35m**preemptive** behavior.[0m
[30;1m77 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m65 | [0m[35mA **greenlet** is a lightweight **coroutine** for in-process sequential[0m
[30;1m66 | [0m[35mconcurrent programming (see **concurrency**). You can usually think of[0m
[30;1m67 | [0m[35mgreenlets as cooperatively scheduled **threads**. The major differences are[0m
[30;1m68 | [0m[35mthat since they’re cooperatively scheduled, you are in control of when they[0m
[30;1m69 | [0m[35mexecute, and since they are **coroutines**, many greenlets can exist in a[0m
[30;1m70 | [0m[35msingle native **thread**.[0m
[30;1m71 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m127 | [0m[35m**Preemptive multitasking** involves the use of an interrupt mechanism which[0m
[30;1m128 | [0m[35msuspends the currently executing process and invokes a scheduler to determine[0m
[30;1m129 | [0m[35mwhich process should execute next. Therefore, all processes will get some[0m
[30;1m130 | [0m[35mamount of CPU time at any given time.[0m

[30;1m133 | [0m[35muninterrupted for 1000 bytecode instructions in Python 2, or runs 15[0m

[30;1m204 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m205 | [0m[35m    It does this by telling the kernel to raise a SIGALARM after a[0m
[30;1m206 | [0m[35m    short timeout, and clearing the timeout every time the hub[0m
[30;1m207 | [0m[35m    greenlet is resumed.  Therefore, any code that runs for a long[0m
[30;1m208 | [0m[35m    time without yielding to the hub will get interrupted by the[0m
[30;1m209 | [0m[35m    blocking detector (don't use it in production!).[0m

[30;1m86 | [0m[35m    greenthread until a value is available for each of the keys specified in[0m
[30;1m87 | [0m[35m    its initial dependencies iterable. These (key, value) pairs are delivered[0m

[30;1m293 | [0m[35m# The _getdate() routine is used to set the expiration time in the cookie's HTTP[0m
[30;1m294 | [0m[35m# header.  By default, _getdate() returns the current time in the appropriate[0m

[30;1m60 | [0m[35m    def ready(self):[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35m        """ Return true if the :meth:`wait` call will return immediately.[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35m        Used to avoid waiting for things that might take a while to time out.[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35m        For example, you can put a bunch of events into a list, and then visit[0m
[30;1m64 | [0m[35m        them all repeatedly, calling :meth:`ready` until one returns ``True``,[0m
[30;1m65 | [0m[35m        and then you can :meth:`wait` on that one."""[0m
